case_name: Yenumula Mallu Dora v. Petitioning Creditors

facts.text: Civil Appeal No. 474 of 1964 filed by special leave from Andhra Pradesh High Court judgment dated March 14, 1963 in C.R.P. No. 1725 of 1959.

anchor.surface_text: CIVIL APPELLATE JURISDICTION Civil Appeal No. 474 of 1964. Appeal by special leave from the judgment and order dated March 14, 1963 of the Andhra Pradesh High Court in C.R.P. No. 1725 of 1959.

facts.text: Yenumula Mallu Dora (appellant) adjudged insolvent by Subordinate Judge, Kakinada with receiving order passed.

anchor.surface_text: On the application of two creditors the appellant Yenumula Mallu Dora has been adjudged insolvent by the Subordinate Judge, Kakinada and a receiving order has been passed against him.

facts.text: Respondents are one petitioning creditor and legal representatives of the other petitioning creditor who died during proceedings.

anchor.surface_text: The respondents before us are one of the petitioning creditors and the legal representatives of the other petitioning creditor who died during these proceedings.

facts.text: First petitioning creditor held decree for money in O.S. 67 of 1949 and another in O.S. 473 of 1948.

anchor.surface_text: The first petitioning creditor held a decree for money which he had obtained in O.S. 67 of 1949. He also held another money decree in O.S. 473 of 1948.

facts.text: Second petitioning creditor held decree obtained in S. 17 of 1955.

anchor.surface_text: The second petitioning creditor held a decree which she had obtained in S. 17 of 1955.

facts.text: Insolvency application based on three acts of insolvency and indebtedness of Rs. two lakhs, unable to pay debts.

anchor.surface_text: The application was based upon three acts of insolvency which the appellant was stated to have companymitted and on the general facts that he was indebted to the tune of Rs. two lakhs, and was unable to pay his debts.

facts.text: First alleged act of insolvency: evasion of arrest in execution of money decree in O.S. 67 of 1949.

anchor.surface_text: The three acts of insolvency alleged against him were  a  evasion of arrest in execution of the money decree in O.S. 67 of 1949

facts.text: Second alleged act: sale of properties on September 26, 1956 in execution from O.S. 73 of 1952.

anchor.surface_text: b  sale of some of his properties on September 26, 1956 in execution arising from O.S. 73 of 1952

facts.text: Third alleged act: sale of properties on September 19, 1956 in execution of money decree in O.S. 9 of 1950.

anchor.surface_text: and  c  sale of some of his properties on September 19, 1956 in execution of money decree in O.S. 9 of 1950.

facts.text: Alleged fraudulent transfers of properties to wife and brother-in-law, collusive charge decree for maintenance to wife.

anchor.surface_text: It was also alleged that he was fraudulently transferring properties in the name of his wife and brother-in-law and had suffered a companylusive charge decree for maintenance in favour of his wife, to delay and defeat his creditors.

facts.text: Subordinate Judge rejected first two acts of insolvency: evasion not convincing, second sale in mortgage decree execution.

anchor.surface_text: The Subordinate Judge, Kakinada did number accept the first two acts of insolvency. The evidence regarding evasion of arrest was number found companyvincing and the second act of insolvency was rejected because the sale of the property was in execution of a mortgage decree.

facts.text: Subordinate Judge held third act satisfies S. 6(e) of Provincial Insolvency Act, justified adjudication and receiving order.

anchor.surface_text: In respect of the third art of insolvency the Subordinate Judge held that it satisfied S. 6 e  of the Provincial Insolvency Act and an adjudication and a receiving order were justified in the case.

facts.text: Appeal to District Court Rajahmundry C.A. 41 of 1958 dismissed on October 15, 1959.
